### PHP switch Statement

The `switch` statement selects one of many code blocks to execute based on a value.

### Syntax

```php
<?php
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // code for value1
        break;
    case value2:
        // code for value2
        break;
    default:
        // code if no case matches
}
?>
```

### Example

```php
<?php
$day = "Monday";

switch ($day) {
    case "Monday":
        echo "Start of the week";
        break;
    case "Friday":
        echo "TGIF";
        break;
    case "Saturday":
    case "Sunday":
        echo "Weekend!";
        break;
    default:
        echo "Midweek";
}
?>
```

### Important Notes

| Aspect | Details |
|--------|---------|
| Break | Required to prevent fall-through |
| Default | Optional, runs if no case matches |
| Fall-through | Omitting `break` continues to next case |
| Comparison | Uses loose comparison (`==`) |

> **Key Point:** Without `break`, PHP continues executing the next case (fall-through). This can be useful but is often a source of bugs.
